# Day/Night Toggle UX/UI Rules

## Icon Semantics
- **Show destination, not current state**: The icon displays what the user will switch TO (sun = switch to light, moon = switch to dark), not the current theme.
- **Consistent mapping**: Sun icon = light mode; Moon icon = dark mode. Never invert or confuse these.

## Accessibility
- Always provide `aria-label` describing the action: "Switch to light mode" or "Switch to dark mode".
- Include `title` for hover tooltip with the same text.
- Ensure minimum 44×44px touch target for the toggle button.
- Use `role="toolbar"` on the parent when grouped with other controls (e.g. language toggle).

## Visual Feedback
- Toggle must have visible hover and focus states (`hover:bg-*`, `focus:ring-2`, etc.).
- Use smooth `transition-colors` when changing theme; avoid jarring flashes.
- Toggle container must work in both themes: use `dark:` variants for borders, backgrounds, and dividers.

## Theme Propagation
- When `.dark` is on `<html>`, all surfaces must update: page background, form panels, cards, inputs, text.
- Use semantic CSS variables (`--color-bg-primary`, `--color-text-primary`) in `.dark` so components inherit correctly.
- Never hardcode light-only values in base styles; always provide `.dark` overrides for `html` and `body`.

## Form & Panel Styling
- Form panels (e.g. Add Content) must have dark variants: `dark:bg-*`, `dark:border-*`, `dark:text-*`.
- Input fields, labels, placeholders, and borders need explicit dark mode classes.
- Light green/beige panels in light mode → use darker greens/grays in dark mode (e.g. `dark:bg-gray-900/50`).

## Hydration
- Delay rendering theme-dependent UI until mounted (`useEffect` + `mounted` state) to avoid hydration mismatch with `next-themes`.
- Show a neutral placeholder (e.g. `animate-pulse`) before mount.

## Implementation Checklist
- [ ] Icon shows destination (sun → light, moon → dark)
- [ ] aria-label and title present
- [ ] 44×44px minimum touch target
- [ ] Hover/focus states visible
- [ ] Base styles (html, body) have `.dark` overrides
- [ ] Utility classes (card-brand, etc.) have dark variants
- [ ] Form panels and inputs support dark mode
- [ ] Mounted check before rendering theme-dependent UI
